text_content:
Just going to put this here after reading some comments;

Ive seen the full video before. The parents never, ever leave their child unsupervised with the snakes. Shes always supervised and was taught what to do if she needed help with either of them. Snakes arent just "children-hungry monsters". I'm not going to deny, some events unfortunately happen. But a snake doesnt snap. Hence the cat reference. Cats kinda flip to whatever mood (orange cats for example lol) and do things quickly. A snake wont if its cared for and not being threatened, and even then, like a cat, a snake will give a warning before doing anything. (Hissing, coiling, puffing up, etc.) 

Im jealous this kid gets such a unique and interesting upbringing getting to learn and experience how to care for these beautiful animals. I was raised in a home where snakes were "evil" and "bloodthirsty". Im happy to say i have plans to get my first snake sometime soon. Hope this family continues to embrace learning about these amazing animals.
